Forensics Evidence Collection > [[Topic 3: Disk Acquisition: Write-Blocking]]

Now that you have captured a memory image (volatile data), the next step is to pull off the power cable, remove the hard disk and capture a triage image, followed by a raw disk image.  But why do we cut power first? To preserve disk content in its current state and prevent possible changes. A clean shutdown would destroy potential evidence as it will change timestamps and overwrite important information. 
 

A portable Tableau forensic write-blocker attached to a hard disk drive

Another reason for cutting power is that acquiring a disk image should be done (ideally) using write-blocking devices, which require the disk to be offline. Write-blocking devices are used to prevent modification of the original evidence during acquisition. While this is the ideal method, it will not always be possible. The high demands of business operations may not allow taking the subject system down.
